I'll help you create a Node.js project to set up Swagger documentation based on your Postman collection. Here's a step-by-step guide:

1. First, let's create a new project structure:

```bash
mkdir onramp-api-docs
cd onramp-api-docs
npm init -y
```

2. Install the required dependencies:

```bash
npm install express swagger-ui-express postman-to-openapi yamljs
```

3. Create the following files:

```javascript:src/index.js
const express = require('express');
const swaggerUi = require('swagger-ui-express');
const YAML = require('yamljs');
const path = require('path');
const postmanToOpenApi = require('postman-to-openapi');

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

// Convert Postman collection to OpenAPI
async function generateOpenAPI() {
  try {
    // Path to your Postman collection
    const postmanCollection = path.join(__dirname, '../test.json');
    // Output path for OpenAPI spec
    const outputFile = path.join(__dirname, '../swagger.yml');

    // Convert Postman collection to OpenAPI
    await postmanToOpenApi(postmanCollection, outputFile, {
      defaultTag: 'General',
    });

    // Load the OpenAPI spec
    const swaggerDocument = YAML.load(outputFile);
    return swaggerDocument;
  } catch (err) {
    console.log('Error converting Postman collection:', err);
    throw err;
  }
}

// Set up Swagger UI
app.use('/api-docs', async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const swaggerDocument = await generateOpenAPI();
    swaggerUi.setup(swaggerDocument)(req, res, next);
  } catch (err) {
    next(err);
  }
});

app.use('/api-docs', swaggerUi.serve);

// Health check endpoint
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'OK' });
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`API documentation server running at http://localhost:${port}/api-docs`);
});
```

4. Update your package.json:

```json:package.json
{
  "name": "onramp-api-docs",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "API documentation using Swagger UI",
  "main": "src/index.js",
  "scripts": {
    "start": "node src/index.js",
    "dev": "nodemon src/index.js"
  },
  "keywords": [],
  "author": "",
  "license": "ISC",
  "dependencies": {
    "express": "^4.18.2",
    "postman-to-openapi": "^3.0.1",
    "swagger-ui-express": "^5.0.0",
    "yamljs": "^0.3.0"
  },
  "devDependencies": {
    "nodemon": "^3.0.2"
  }
}
```

5. Copy your test.json file to the project root.

6. Create a .gitignore file:

```text:.gitignore
node_modules/
swagger.yml
```

```

2. Start the server:

```

3. For development with auto-reload:
```bash

```

4. Access the Swagger documentation:
- Open your browser and go to: http://localhost:3000/api-docs

The server will:

3. Serve the Swagger UI with your API documentation

_**Assistant**_

The errors you're seeing are related to missing static files that Swagger UI needs. Let's modify the index.js file to serve these static files correctly:

```javascript:src/index.js
const express = require('express');
const swaggerUi = require('swagger-ui-express');
const YAML = require('yamljs');
const path = require('path');
const postmanToOpenApi = require('postman-to-openapi');

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

// Serve swagger-ui static files
app.use('/api-docs', express.static(path.join(__dirname, '../node_modules/swagger-ui-express/static')));

// Convert Postman collection to OpenAPI
async function generateOpenAPI() {
  try {
    const postmanCollection = path.join(__dirname, '../test.json');
    const outputFile = path.join(__dirname, '../swagger.yml');

    await postmanToOpenApi(postmanCollection, outputFile, {
      defaultTag: 'General',
    });

    const swaggerDocument = YAML.load(outputFile);
    return swaggerDocument;
  } catch (err) {
    console.log('Error converting Postman collection:', err);
    throw err;
  }
}

// Set up Swagger UI
app.use('/api-docs', async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const swaggerDocument = await generateOpenAPI();
    const swaggerOptions = {
      explorer: true,
      swaggerOptions: {
        urls: [
          {
            url: '/api-docs/swagger.json',
            name: 'API Documentation'
          }
        ]
      }
    };
    swaggerUi.setup(swaggerDocument, swaggerOptions)(req, res, next);
  } catch (err) {
    next(err);
  }
});

// Serve swagger.json
app.get('/api-docs/swagger.json', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const swaggerDocument = await generateOpenAPI();
    res.json(swaggerDocument);
  } catch (err) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: err.message });
  }
});

app.use('/api-docs', swaggerUi.serve);

// Health check endpoint
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'OK' });
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`API documentation server running at http://localhost:${port}/api-docs`);
});
```

The key changes made are:

1. Added static file serving for Swagger UI files
2. Added proper configuration for Swagger UI setup
3. Added an endpoint to serve the swagger.json file

To test this:

1. Stop your current server if it's running
2. Start it again with:
```bash
npm start
```

3. Access the documentation at:
```
http://localhost:3000/api-docs
```

This should now load without the 404 errors for the JavaScript files. The Swagger UI interface should be fully functional with all styles and interactive features working properly.

If you still see any issues, make sure:

1. All dependencies are installed correctly:
```bash
rm -rf node_modules
npm install
```

2. The test.json file exists in your project root directory
3. The server has write permissions to create swagger.yml

Let me know if you still encounter any issues!

_**Assistant**_

Let's fix the MIME type and static file serving issues. Here's the corrected version of index.js:

```javascript:src/index.js
const express = require('express');
const swaggerUi = require('swagger-ui-express');
const YAML = require('yamljs');
const path = require('path');
const postmanToOpenApi = require('postman-to-openapi');

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

// Convert Postman collection to OpenAPI
async function generateOpenAPI() {
  try {
    const postmanCollection = path.join(__dirname, '../test.json');
    const outputFile = path.join(__dirname, '../swagger.yml');

    await postmanToOpenApi(postmanCollection, outputFile, {
      defaultTag: 'General',
    });

    const swaggerDocument = YAML.load(outputFile);
    return swaggerDocument;
  } catch (err) {
    console.log('Error converting Postman collection:', err);
    throw err;
  }
}

// Initialize swagger-document
let swaggerDocument;
(async () => {
  try {
    swaggerDocument = await generateOpenAPI();
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Failed to generate OpenAPI document:', err);
  }
})();

// Configure swagger options
const swaggerOptions = {
  explorer: true,
  customCss: '.swagger-ui .topbar { display: none }',
  customSiteTitle: "OnRamp API Documentation"
};

// Set up Swagger UI
app.use('/api-docs', swaggerUi.serve);
app.get('/api-docs', swaggerUi.setup(swaggerDocument, swaggerOptions));

// Health check endpoint
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'OK' });
});

// Error handling middleware
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Something broke!' });
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`API documentation server running at http://localhost:${port}/api-docs`);
});
```

The main changes are:

1. Simplified the Swagger UI setup
2. Removed redundant static file serving
3. Added proper error handling
4. Generated the swagger document once at startup
5. Added proper swagger options configuration

I'll help you create a Swagger setup from scratch without using the Postman collection. Let's create a new project with proper OpenAPI/Swagger documentation.

1. First, let's create a new project structure:
```bash
mkdir swagger-api-docs
cd swagger-api-docs
npm init -y
```

2. Install the required dependencies:
```bash
npm install express swagger-ui-express swagger-jsdoc yamljs
npm install --save-dev nodemon
```

3. Create the project structure:
```bash
mkdir src
mkdir src/routes
mkdir src/swagger
```

Let's create the necessary files:

```javascript:src/index.js
const express = require('express');
const swaggerUi = require('swagger-ui-express');
const swaggerJsdoc = require('swagger-jsdoc');

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

// Swagger definition
const swaggerOptions = {
  definition: {
    openapi: '3.0.0',
    info: {
      title: 'OnRamp API Documentation',
      version: '1.0.0',
      description: 'API documentation for OnRamp services',
      contact: {
        name: 'API Support',
        url: 'https://onramp.money',
        email: 'support@onramp.money'
      }
    },
    servers: [
      {
        url: 'https://api-test.onramp.money',
        description: 'Sandbox Environment'
      },
      {
        url: 'https://api.onramp.money',
        description: 'Production Environment'
      }
    ],
    components: {
      securitySchemes: {
        ApiKeyAuth: {
          type: 'apiKey',
          in: 'header',
          name: 'apiKey'
        },
        SignatureAuth: {
          type: 'apiKey',
          in: 'header',
          name: 'signature'
        },
        PayloadAuth: {
          type: 'apiKey',
          in: 'header',
          name: 'payload'
        }
      }
    },
    security: [
      {
        ApiKeyAuth: [],
        SignatureAuth: [],
        PayloadAuth: []
      }
    ]
  },
  apis: ['./src/routes/*.js', './src/swagger/*.js']
};

const swaggerSpec = swaggerJsdoc(swaggerOptions);

// Serve swagger docs
app.use('/api-docs', swaggerUi.serve);
app.use('/api-docs', swaggerUi.setup(swaggerSpec, {
  explorer: true,
  customCss: '.swagger-ui .topbar { display: none }',
  customSiteTitle: "OnRamp API Documentation"
}));

// Health check endpoint
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'OK' });
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`API documentation server running at http://localhost:${port}/api-docs`);
});
```

```javascript:src/swagger/schemas.js
/**
 * @swagger
 * components:
 *   schemas:
 *     Error:
 *       type: object
 *       properties:
 *         status:
 *           type: integer
 *           example: 0
 *         code:
 *           type: integer
 *           example: 400
 *         error:
 *           type: string
 *           example: "Missing required parameters"
 *     SuccessResponse:
 *       type: object
 *       properties:
 *         status:
 *           type: integer
 *           example: 1
 *         code:
 *           type: integer
 *           example: 200
 *         data:
 *           type: object
 */
```

```javascript:src/routes/user.js
/**
 * @swagger
 * /whiteLabel/user/limit:
 *   post:
 *     tags:
 *       - User
 *     summary: Get user limits
 *     description: Retrieve the transaction limits for a user
 *     requestBody:
 *       required: true
 *       content:
 *         application/x-www-form-urlencoded:
 *           schema:
 *             type: object
 *             required:
 *               - customerId
 *               - fiatType
 *             properties:
 *               customerId:
 *                 type: string
 *                 description: Unique identifier for the customer
 *               fiatType:
 *                 type: string
 *                 description: Type of fiat currency
 *     responses:
 *       200:
 *         description: Success
 *         content:
 *           application/json:
 *             schema:
 *               $ref: '#/components/schemas/SuccessResponse'
 *       400:
 *         description: Bad Request
 *         content:
 *           application/json:
 *             schema:
 *               $ref: '#/components/schemas/Error'
 */
```

```javascript:src/routes/kyb.js
/**
 * @swagger
 * /whiteLabel/kyb/requirements:
 *   get:

 *     parameters:
 *       - in: query
 *         name: country
 *         required: true
 *         schema:
 *           type: string
 *         description: Country code (e.g., IND)
 *     responses:
 *       200:

 *         content:
 *           application/json:
 *             schema:
 *               $ref: '#/components/schemas/SuccessResponse'
 *       400:
 *         description: Bad Request

 *           application/json:
 *             schema:
 *               $ref: '#/components/schemas/Error'
 * 
 * /whiteLabel/kyb/submit:
 *   post:
 *     tags:
 *       - KYB
 *     summary: Submit KYB details
 *     description: Submit KYB information for verification
 *     requestBody:
 *       required: true
 *       content:
 *         application/x-www-form-urlencoded:
 *           schema:
 *             type: object
 *             required:
 *               - customerId
 *               - entityName

 *             properties:

 *                 type: string
 *                 description: Unique identifier for the customer
 *               entityName:
 *                 type: string

 */
```

/**
 * @swagger
 * /whiteLabel/kyb/requirements:

 *         description: Bad Request

 *           application/json:
 *             schema:
 *               $ref: '#/components/schemas/Error'
 * 
 * /whiteLabel/kyb/submit:
 *   post:
 *     tags:
 *       - KYB

 *     requestBody:
 *       required: true
 *       content:
 *         application/x-www-form-urlencoded:
 *           schema:
 *             type: object
 *             required:
 *               - customerId
 *               - entityName
 *               - legalEntityNature
 *             properties:
 *               customerId:
 *                 type: string
 *                 description: Unique identifier for the customer
 *               entityName:
 *                 type: string
 *                 description: Name of the entity
 *               legalEntityNature:
 *                 type: string
 *                 description: Nature of the legal entity
 *     responses:
 *       200:
 *         description: Success
 *         content:
 *           application/json:
 *             schema:
 *               $ref: '#/components/schemas/SuccessResponse'
 *       400:
 *         description: Bad Request
 *         content:
 *           application/json:
 *             schema:

4. Update the index.js with security schemes:

```javascript:src/index.js
const express = require('express');
const swaggerUi = require('swagger-ui-express');
const swaggerJsdoc = require('swagger-jsdoc');

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

// Swagger definition
const swaggerOptions = {
  definition: {
    openapi: '3.0.0',
    info: {
      title: 'OnRamp API Documentation',
      version: '1.0.0',
      description: 'API documentation for OnRamp services',
      contact: {
        name: 'API Support',
        url: 'https://onramp.money',
        email: 'support@onramp.money'
      }
    },
    servers: [
      {
        url: 'https://api-test.onramp.money',
        description: 'Sandbox Environment'
      },
      {
        url: 'https://api.onramp.money',
        description: 'Production Environment'
      }
    ],
    components: {
      securitySchemes: {
        ApiKeyAuth: {
          type: 'apiKey',
          in: 'header',
          name: 'apiKey'
        },
        SignatureAuth: {
          type: 'apiKey',
          in: 'header',
          name: 'signature'
        },
        PayloadAuth: {
          type: 'apiKey',
          in: 'header',
          name: 'payload'
        }
      }
    },
    security: [
      {
        ApiKeyAuth: [],
        SignatureAuth: [],
        PayloadAuth: []
      }
    ]
  },
  apis: ['./src/routes/*.js', './src/swagger/*.js']
};

const swaggerSpec = swaggerJsdoc(swaggerOptions);

// Serve swagger docs
app.use('/api-docs', swaggerUi.serve);
app.use('/api-docs', swaggerUi.setup(swaggerSpec, {
  explorer: true,
  customCss: '.swagger-ui .topbar { display: none }',
  customSiteTitle: "OnRamp API Documentation"
}));

// Health check endpoint
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'OK' });
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`API documentation server running at http://localhost:${port}/api-docs`);
});
```

The documentation will be available at http://localhost:3000/api-docs when you run the server.

{"swagger":"2.0","info":{"contact":{},"description":"# Authenticate Request\n\n##### Every request is authenticated via verifying signature, payload and apiKey.\n\n##### `Note: Add apiKey, signature and payload in every request header.`\n\n##### Sample header to add API key, Signature and Payload\n\n``` json\nconst headers = {\n      'apikey': apiKey,\n      'payload': payload,\n      'signature': signature,\n};\n\n```\n\n# Generate Payload and Signature\n\n``` javascript\nconst CryptoJS = require('crypto-js');\nasync function generatePayloadAndSignature(secret, body) {\n  const timestamp = Date.now().toString();\n  const obj = {\n    body,\n    timestamp\n  };\n  const payload = CryptoJS.enc.Base64.stringify(CryptoJS.enc.Utf8.parse(JSON.stringify(obj)));\n  const signature = CryptoJS.enc.Hex.stringify(CryptoJS.HmacSHA512(payload, secret));\n  return { payload, signature };\n}\n\n```\n\n# Sandbox Environment\n\n### Sandbox Endpoint URL\n\n##### When accessing the sandbox environment, use the endpoint URL\n\n`api-test.onramp.money` instead of `api.onramp.money`\n\n### Credential Distinction\n\n##### In the sandbox environment, exclusive use of sandbox credentials is required; production environment credentials will result in unauthorized.\n\n### Auth Process\n\n##### The auth process remains consistent with that of the production environment.\n\n# Webhook Setup\n\n##### In order for Liquidity Partners to notify Client of status updates during workflows such as KYB/KYC, Onramp and Offramp, Client will provide the API endpoint to send webhooks.  *         1. apiKey - Your API key

 *         3. payload - Base64 encoded JSON containing request body and timestamp

_**Assistant**_



Let me help you create a proper authorization module. We'll create two files:

```javascript:src/auth/generateHeaders.js
/**
 * Generates authentication headers for API requests
 * @param {string} apiKey - Your API key
 * @param {string} secret - Your API secret
 * @param {Object} body - Request body
 * @returns {Object} Headers object with apiKey, payload, signature and timestamp
 */
const CryptoJS = require('crypto-js');

const generateHeaders = (apiKey, secret, body = {}) => {
    const timestamp = Date.now().toString();
    const obj = { body, timestamp };
    
    const payload = CryptoJS.enc.Base64.stringify(
        CryptoJS.enc.Utf8.parse(JSON.stringify(obj))
    );
    
    const signature = CryptoJS.enc.Hex.stringify(
        CryptoJS.HmacSHA512(payload, secret)
    );

    return {
        apiKey,
        payload,
        signature,
        timestamp
    };
};

module.exports = generateHeaders;
```

```javascript:src/auth/authorize.js
const generateHeaders = require('./generateHeaders');

/**
 * Adds authentication headers to your request
 * @param {string} apiKey - Your API key
 * @param {string} secret - Your API secret
 * @param {Object} requestConfig - Axios request config object
 * @returns {Object} Updated request config with auth headers
 */
const authorize = (apiKey, secret) => {
    return (requestConfig) => {
        const body = requestConfig.data || {};
        const headers = generateHeaders(apiKey, secret, body);
        
        return {
            ...requestConfig,
            headers: {
                ...requestConfig.headers,
                ...headers
            }
        };
    };
};

module.exports = authorize;
```

Then you can use it like this:

```javascript:src/index.js
const axios = require('axios');
const authorize = require('./auth/authorize');

// Initialize with your credentials
const apiKey = 'YOUR_API_KEY';
const secret = 'YOUR_SECRET';

// Create an axios instance with auth
const api = axios.create({
    baseURL: 'https://api-test.onramp.money',
});

// Add the authorize interceptor
api.interceptors.request.use(authorize(apiKey, secret));

// Now you can make requests and headers will be added automatically
const makeRequest = async () => {
    try {
        const response = await api.post('/whiteLabel/kyc/submit', {
            customerId: 'example123',
            // ... other data
        });
        console.log(response.data);
    } catch (error) {
        console.error(error);
    }
};
```

For Postman, you can still use the pre-request script:

```javascript:src/swagger/auth.js
/**
 * @swagger
 * components:
 *   securitySchemes:
 *     WhiteLabelAuth:
 *       description: |
 *         ```javascript
 *         // Set your credentials
 *         const apiKey = "YOUR_API_KEY"; 
 *         const secret = "YOUR_SECRET";
 *         
 *         // Get request body
 *         let body = {};
 *         if(pm.request.body.urlencoded) {
 *             body = pm.request.body.urlencoded.reduce((data, param) => {
 *                 data[param.key] = param.value;
 *                 return data;
 *             }, {});   
 *         } else if(pm.request.body.formdata) {
 *             body = pm.request.body.formdata.reduce((data, param) => {
 *                 data[param.key] = param.value;
 *                 return data;
 *             }, {});
 *         }
 *         
 *         // Generate and set headers
 *         const timestamp = Date.now().toString();
 *         const obj = { body, timestamp };
 *         const payload = CryptoJS.enc.Base64.stringify(CryptoJS.enc.Utf8.parse(JSON.stringify(obj)));
 *         const signature = CryptoJS.enc.Hex.stringify(CryptoJS.HmacSHA512(payload, secret));
 *         
 *         pm.request.headers.add({ key: "apiKey", value: apiKey });
 *         pm.request.headers.add({ key: "payload", value: payload });
 *         pm.request.headers.add({ key: "signature", value: signature });
 *         pm.request.headers.add({ key: "timestamp", value: timestamp });
 *         ```
 */
```

This setup:
1. Provides a reusable authentication module
2. Works with both Node.js applications and Postman
3. Automatically adds required headers to all requests
4. Keeps credentials in one place

Let me know if you need any clarification or adjustments!

            params.append('phoneNumber', phoneNumber || '+919876543210');
            
            const response = await api.post('/whiteLabel/kyc/url', params);
            
            res.json(response.data);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('KYC URL Error:', {
                status: error.response?.status,
                data: error.response?.data,
                message: error.message
            });
            res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
                error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
            });
        }
    });

    return router;
};

module.exports = createKycRouter;

Ah, I understand now. Let's update the authorize middleware to properly add these headers:

```javascript:src/auth/authorize.js
const generateHeaders = require('./generateHeaders');

/**
 * Adds authentication headers to your request
 * @param {string} apiKey - Your API key
 * @param {string} secret - Your API secret
 * @param {Object} requestConfig - Axios request config object
 * @returns {Object} Updated request config with auth headers
 */
const authorize = (apiKey, secret) => {
    return (requestConfig) => {
        const body = requestConfig.data || {};
        const timestamp = Date.now().toString();
        const obj = { body, timestamp };
        
        // Generate payload and signature
        const payload = Buffer.from(JSON.stringify(obj)).toString('base64');
        const crypto = require('crypto');
        const signature = crypto.createHmac('sha512', secret).update(payload).digest('hex');

        // Add auth headers
        requestConfig.headers = {
            ...requestConfig.headers,
            'apiKey': apiKey,
            'payload': payload,
            'signature': signature,
            'timestamp': timestamp,
            'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded'
        };

        return requestConfig;
    };
};

module.exports = authorize;
```

Now when making requests in kyc.js, these headers will be automatically added:

```javascript:src/routes/kyc.js

        params.append('clientCustomerId', clientCustomerId);
        params.append('phoneNumber', phoneNumber);
        
        // Headers will be automatically added by the authorize interceptor
        const response = await api.post('/whiteLabel/kyc/url', params);
        
        res.json(response.data);
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('KYC URL Error:', {
            status: error.response?.status,
            data: error.response?.data,
            message: error.message
        });
        res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
            error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
        });
    }
});
```

The authorize interceptor will now:
1. Generate timestamp
2. Create payload from body and timestamp
3. Generate signature using HMAC-SHA512
4. Add all required headers:
   - apiKey
   - payload
   - signature
   - timestamp
   - Content-Type

Let's check the authorize middleware and make sure it's properly adding all headers. Let's update the authorize.js file:

```javascript:src/auth/authorize.js
const crypto = require('crypto');

/**
 * Adds authentication headers to your request
 * @param {string} apiKey - Your API key
 * @param {string} secret - Your API secret
 * @param {Object} requestConfig - Axios request config object
 * @returns {Object} Updated request config with auth headers
 */
const authorize = (apiKey, secret) => {
    return (requestConfig) => {
        console.log('Request Config Before:', requestConfig);

        // Get request body
        const body = requestConfig.data || {};
        
        // Generate timestamp and create payload object
        const timestamp = Date.now().toString();
        const obj = { body, timestamp };
        
        // Generate payload and signature
        const payload = Buffer.from(JSON.stringify(obj)).toString('base64');
        const signature = crypto.createHmac('sha512', secret).update(payload).digest('hex');

        // Add all required headers
        requestConfig.headers = {
            ...requestConfig.headers,
            'apiKey': apiKey,
            'payload': payload,
            'signature': signature,
            'timestamp': timestamp,
            'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded'
        };

        console.log('Generated Headers:', {
            apiKey,
            payload,
            signature,
            timestamp
        });

        console.log('Request Config After:', requestConfig);

        return requestConfig;
    };
};

module.exports = authorize;
```

 *                 example: "vqzubP9504_3491"
 *               phoneNumber:
 *                 type: string
 *                 description: Must start with '+' and contain only numbers
 *                 example: "+919876543210"
 *               type:
 *                 type: string
 *                 enum: [INDIVIDUAL]
 *                 default: INDIVIDUAL
 *                 example: "INDIVIDUAL"
 *               closeAfterLogin:
 *                 type: boolean
 *                 default: true
 *                 example: true
 *     responses:
 *       200:
 *         description: Success
 *         content:
 *           application/json:
 *             schema:
 *               type: object
 *               properties:
 *                 clientCustomerId:
 *                   type: string
 *                 customerId:
 *                   type: string
 *                 kycUrl:
 *                   type: string
 */

// ... rest of the code ...
```

Now the Swagger UI will:

```javascript:src/routes/onramp.js
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();
const axios = require('axios');
const authorize = require('../auth/authorize');

const createOnrampRouter = (apiKey, secret) => {
    const externalApi = axios.create({
        baseURL: 'https://api-test.onramp.money',
        headers: {
            'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded',
            'Accept': 'application/json'
        }
    });

    externalApi.interceptors.request.use(authorize(apiKey, secret));

    router.post('/onramp/quote', async (req, res) => {
        try {
            console.log("Request received at /onramp/quote");
            const requestBody = req.body;
            
            console.log('Making request to external API with body:', requestBody);
            
            const response = await externalApi.post('/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/onramp/quote', requestBody);
            
            console.log('External API Response:', {
                status: response.status,
                headers: response.headers,
                data: response.data
            });
            
            res.json(response.data);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('Onramp Quote Error:', {
                status: error.response?.status,
                data: error.response?.data,
                headers: error.response?.headers,
                message: error.message
            });
            res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
                error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
            });
        }
    });

    return router;
};

module.exports = createOnrampRouter;

I'll help you add all the missing endpoints from the Postman collection. Let's start by adding the KYB routes since they're well documented in the collection:

```javascript:src/routes/kyb.js
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();
const axios = require('axios');
const authorize = require('../auth/authorize');

const createKybRouter = (apiKey, secret) => {
    const externalApi = axios.create({
        baseURL: 'https://api-test.onramp.money',
        headers: {
            'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded',
            'Accept': 'application/json'
        }
    });

    externalApi.interceptors.request.use(authorize(apiKey, secret));

    // Get KYB Requirements
    router.get('/kyb/requirements', async (req, res) => {
        try {
            const { country } = req.query;
            if (!country) {
                return res.status(400).json({
                    status: 0,
                    code: 400,
                    error: "country is missing!"
                });
            }

            const response = await externalApi.get(`/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/kyb/requirements?country=${country}`);
            res.json(response.data);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('KYB Requirements Error:', error);
            res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
                error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
            });
        }
    });

    // Submit KYB
    router.post('/kyb/submit', async (req, res) => {
        try {
            const response = await externalApi.post('/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/kyb/submit', req.body);
            res.json(response.data);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('KYB Submit Error:', error);
            res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
                error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
            });
        }
    });

    // Check KYB Status
    router.post('/kyb/status', async (req, res) => {
        try {
            const response = await externalApi.post('/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/kyb/status', req.body);
            res.json(response.data);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('KYB Status Error:', error);
            res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
                error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
            });
        }
    });

    // Change KYB Status
    router.post('/kyb/changeStatus', async (req, res) => {
        try {
            const response = await externalApi.post('/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/kyb/changeStatus', req.body);
            res.json(response.data);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('KYB Change Status Error:', error);
            res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
                error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
            });
        }
    });

    return router;
};

module.exports = createKybRouter;
```

```javascript:src/routes/kyc.js
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();
const axios = require('axios');
const authorize = require('../auth/authorize');

const createKycRouter = (apiKey, secret) => {
    const externalApi = axios.create({
        baseURL: 'https://api-test.onramp.money',
        headers: {
            'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded',
            'Accept': 'application/json'
        }
    });

    externalApi.interceptors.request.use(authorize(apiKey, secret));

    // Get KYC URL
    router.post('/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/kyc/url', async (req, res) => {
        try {
            console.log("Request received at /kyc/url");
            const { clientCustomerId, phoneNumber } = req.body;
            
            const requestBody = {
                clientCustomerId,
                phoneNumber,
                type: 'INDIVIDUAL',
                closeAfterLogin: true
            };
            
            console.log('Making request to external API with body:', requestBody);
            
            const response = await externalApi.post('/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/kyc/url', requestBody);
            
            console.log('External API Response:', {
                status: response.status,
                headers: response.headers,
                data: response.data
            });
            
            res.json(response.data);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('KYC URL Error:', error);
            res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
                error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
            });
        }
    });

    // Check KYC Status
    router.post('/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/kyc/status', async (req, res) => {
        try {
            console.log("Request received at /kyc/status");
            const requestBody = req.body;
            
            console.log('Making request to external API with body:', requestBody);
            
            const response = await externalApi.post('/onramp/api/v2/whiteLabel/kyc/status', requestBody);
            
            console.log('External API Response:', {
                status: response.status,
                headers: response.headers,
                data: response.data
            });
            
            res.json(response.data);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('KYC Status Error:', error);
            res.status(error.response?.status || 500).json({
                error: error.response?.data?.error || error.message
            });
        }
    });

    return router;
};

module.exports = createKycRouter;
